"v. 游荡；徘徊 【英】 v. 游荡(to linger)；走走停停(to walk or move slowly and indolently 【例】 The tourists loitered about the town square, browsing through several of the shops. (browsing: 浏览) v. (漫无目的地)游荡; 虚度(光阴) 【记】读: 蝼蚁头儿, 蝼蚁的头儿不用工作, 可以整天游荡! 【记】音：老头；老头可以整天提笼架鸟，四处遛达，游荡 loiter (v.)  early 15c., ""idle one's time, dawdle over work,"" from Middle Dutch loteren ""be loose or erratic, shake, totter"" like a loose tooth or a sail in a storm; in modern Dutch, leuteren ""to delay, linger, loiter over one's work."" Probably cognate with Old English lutian ""lurk,"" and related to Old English loddere ""beggar;"" Old High German lotar ""empty, vain,"" luzen ""lurk;"" German Lotterbube ""vagabond, rascal,"" lauschen ""eavesdrop;"" Gothic luton ""mislead;"" Old English lyðre ""base, bad, wicked."" Related: Loitered; loitering."
